Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
write_path_descriptions(25.10)                  write_path_descriptions(25.10)

Name
       write_path_descriptions  -  Writes out the path descriptions of all the
       timing paths specified in the variable (path collection)  to  an  ASCII
       file

Syntax
       write_path_descriptions

       [-help]

       var_name

       -out_file <string>

       Writes  out  the path descriptions of all the timing paths specified in
       the variable (path collection) to an ASCII file.

       The output file contains a set of report_timing commands for each  tim-
       ing  path  in  the given path collection. The file also includes a com-
       plete description of each timing path captured  through  timing  points
       along with the clock and edge information.

       The  path  description  of a given collection of paths can be read back
       and the same path configuration can be recreated in another Tempus ses-
       sion. This allows to process and compare the  timing,  attributes,  and
       other characteristics of the specified paths.

Parameters
       -help  Prints out the command usage.

       <var_name>
              Specifies the object collection of timing paths.  The input must
              be a single collection.

              If you need to write out path descriptions of collections gener-
              ated with different analysis types or path collections, a single
              collection can be created by appending all the collections using
              the append_to_collection command.

       -out_file <string>
              Redirects output to the specified file.

       Examples
              * The  following  command  writes  out  descriptions of late GBA
                paths - when the -path_type parameter is not specified:

                set path_coll [report_timing -collection]

                write_path_descriptions $path_coll > PathSpecFile.txt

                The output file PathSpecFile.txt contains:

                report_timing -net -path_type full_clock  -late  -from_rise  A
                -through_rise B -through_rise C \

                       -to_rise  D  -view  slow_v  -clock_from clk1 -edge_from
                lead -clock_to clk2 -edge_to lead

              * The following command writes  out  descriptions  of  late  PBA
                paths when the -path_typefull option is specified:

                set     path_coll     [report_timing    -collection    -retime
                path_slew_propagation -path_type full]

                write_path_descriptions $path_coll > PathSpecFile.txt

                The output file PathSpecFile.txt contains:

                report_timing -net -path_type full_clock  -late  -from_rise  A
                -through_rise B -through_rise C \

                       -to_rise  D  -view  slow_v  -clock_from clk1 -edge_from
                lead -clock_to clk2 -edge_to lead

                Note: The output does not show retime details. You should  use
                the  read_path_descriptions-retime parameter to analyze retime
                collections that are defined with the  write_path_descriptions
                command.

              * The  following  command  writes  out  descriptions of both the
                early and late GBA paths:

                set path_coll [report_timing -collection]

                set path_coll_early [report_timing -collection -early]

                append_to_collection path_coll $path_coll_early

                write_path_descriptions $path_coll > PathSpecFile.txt

                The output file PathSpecFile.txt contains:

                report_timing -net -path_type full_clock  -late  -from_rise  A
                -through_rise B -through_rise C \

                       -to_rise  D  -view  slow_v  -clock_from clk1 -edge_from
                lead -clock_to clk2 -edge_to lead

                report_timing -net -path_type full_clock -early  -from_rise  A
                through_rise B -to_rise D -view \

                       slow_v  -clock_from clk1 -edge_from lead -clock_to clk2
                -edge_to lead

